The paper discusses resource management in Grid computing environments, which involves distributed systems and algorithms for scheduling and allocation. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The paper also proposes a computational economy framework for resource allocation, which involves economic models for regulating supply and demand. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the necessary infrastructure for supporting economic models in Grid computing, which involves software engineering and computer engineering principles. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Computer Engineering (cs.CE) and Software Engineering (cs.SE) categories. Finally, the paper discusses optimization strategies for resource brokering, which involves algorithms and data structures for optimization. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category.
